Bloom Filter
A Bloom Filter is a space-efficient, probabilistic data structure used to test whether an element is a member of a set.

The Naive Approach: Keep all billions of usernames in a SQL database or an in-memory HashSet. Checking it takes $O(1)$ time, 
but the memory cost is massive (gigabytes of RAM just storing strings).
The Bloom Filter Approach: You use a tiny bit array in memory. When a username is taken, you flip a few bits to 1.

If the Bloom filter says "No", it is 100% certain that the item has never been seen before. (Zero False Negatives).

If the Bloom filter says "Yes", it means the item has probably been seen before, but there is a slight chance it's a mistake. (Possible False Positives).

How it works - 
A Bloom filter consists of two primary components:
A bit array of size m, initially all set to 0.
A set of k different cryptographically independent hash functions (e.g., MurmurHash, FNV-1a). Each hash function must map an incoming element to one of the m slots in the bit array.

Step A: Adding an ElementWhen you add an item to the filter:Feed the item into each of the $k$ hash functions.Each hash function will output an integer index.
Set the bits at those specific indices in the bit array to 1.Example: Suppose we have a 10-bit array and 3 hash functions ($k=3$). We want to add the 
username "alice":
hash1(alice) = 2
hash2(alice) = 5
hash3(alice)= 8
Bits 2, 5, and 8 are flipped to 1.

Step B: Querying an ElementTo check if an item already exists in the set:
Pass the item through the same $k$ hash functions to get the target indices.Look at the bit array at those indices:
If any of those bits are still 0, the item definitely does not exist in the set (if it did, those bits would have been flipped to 1 during ingestion).
If all of those bits are 1, the filter returns true.

How False Positives Happen
Imagine you check for the username "bob". Its hashes point to indices 2, 5, and 9.
Index 2 and 5 were already set to 1 by "alice" earlier.
If another completely unrelated item happened to set index 9 to 1 in the past, all three bits for "bob" are now 1.
The filter will confidently tell you "bob" exists, even though "bob" was never added. This is a False Positive collision.

Usage:
1. Database Query Avoidance (LSM-Trees, Cassandra, BigTable)
When looking up a row key, databases have to read data from disk files (SSTables). Reading disk is slow. Systems like Apache Cassandra put a small Bloom filter in RAM for each file.
If the filter says the key isn't in that file, the database skips reading that file entirely.
This saves thousands of expensive disk I/O operations per second.

3. Content Recommendations / Cache Filtering (Medium, Squid)
Preventing users from seeing duplicate content. Medium can use a Bloom filter to track 
articles you've already read. When generating your homepage feed, it passes potential articles through your local filter to weed out read content without making heavy database joins.

Pitfals and Limitations - 
1. No Deletions Allowed: You cannot remove an item from a standard Bloom filter. If you try to delete "alice" by flipping bits 2, 5, and 8 back to 0, 
you might inadvertently erase bits that are also shared by other items in your system, introducing catastrophic false negatives.
  The Fix: If you absolutely need deletions, you must use a Counting Bloom Filter, which replaces the binary bits with numerical 
  counters that increment on insertion and decrement on removal.
2. The Filter Fills Up Over Time: The false positive rate ($p$) is a mathematical function of the number of items inserted ($n$), the array size ($m$), and the number of hash functions ($k$). 
If you keep stuffing elements into the filter without expanding it, the array will slowly become mostly 1s, causing the false positive rate to degrade toward $100\%$.
3. Non-Scalable Memory Size: A traditional Bloom filter is static. You must allocate the bit array size upfront based on your projected peak capacity. 
If your dataset grows $10\times$ beyond your estimate, you have to build a new, larger Bloom filter from scratch and re-hash your entire historical database into it.


Count Min Sketch - 
A Count-Min Sketch is a sub-linear, probabilistic data structure used to estimate the frequencies of elements in a massive data stream.

If a Bloom Filter answers a binary "Have I seen this?" question, a Count-Min Sketch answers a frequency question: 
"How many times have I seen this item?" It does this using a tiny, fixed amount of memory, making it an essential tool for big data processing and real-time streaming architectures.
You need to keep track of how many times every IP address or hashtag appears so you can find the "heavy hitters" (the top IP traffic or top trends).

The Naive Approach: Use a standard Hash Map (Map<String, Integer>). Every time a hashtag appears, increment its count.
  The Problem: If there are hundreds of millions of unique hashtags, your hash map will eventually run out of RAM, causing the application to crash.
The Count-Min Sketch Approach: You use a tiny, two-dimensional array of integers in memory. It tracks frequencies by routing elements through multiple hash functions.
  It never underestimates the frequency of an item. (Zero underestimation).
  It may overestimate the frequency of an item due to hash collisions.

how it works - 
A Count-Min Sketch consists of a two-dimensional grid of counters with a width $w$ and a depth $d$:The Grid Matrix: 
A table of dimensions d * w filled with integer counters, initially all set to 0.
Hash Functions: A set of d distinct pairwise independent hash functions. Each row in the matrix is mapped to exactly one unique hash function.

Incrementing an element - 
You pass $x$ through each of the $d$ hash functions.Hash function 1 tells you which column to look at in Row 1. 
You increment that specific counter by 1.Hash function 2 tells you which column to look at in Row 2. 
You increment that counter by 1.You repeat this down through all $d$ rows.

Query the element - 
Pass $x$ through the same $d$ hash functions to locate its associated counter in each row.
Read the values of all d counters.Take the absolute minimum value among all those counters. This minimum value is your estimated frequency.

Why do we take the Minimum?
Because multiple items map to the same grid locations, hash collisions will artificially inflate the counters. For instance, 
a high-frequency item might collide with "NVIDIA" in Row 1, inflating the count at Matrix[0][5].

However, because the hash functions are independent, it is highly unlikely that the same interfering item will collide with "NVIDIA" across all rows. 
Therefore, the row with the lowest value represents the path with the least collision noise, yielding the closest approximation to the true frequency.
use cases - 
1. Identifying Top-K Heavy Hitters (Trending Topics)
2. Network Traffic & DDoS Mitigation - To detect a Distributed Denial of Service (DDoS) attack, the router must track packet frequencies per IP address. A Count-Min Sketch allows
the router to instantly identify if an IP address is hitting it 50,000 times a second without running out of hardware memory.
3. Cache Management (TinyLFU in Caffeine Cache) - High-performance system caching engines use a Count-Min Sketch to track incoming item access frequencies. 
If the cache is full and needs to evict an item,
it queries the sketch to see which item is accessed less frequently across history, maximizing the cache hit ratio while keeping memory footprint under a few kilobytes.

Pitfalls and Limitations
1. Saturated Matrix Error Over Time: As the stream runs continuously, counters only go up. 
If a stream runs indefinitely, the matrix will eventually saturate, causing every query to drastically overestimate frequencies.
Fix - The Fix: Implement a Aging / Decay Mechanism. Periodically (e.g., every 5 minutes or every 100,000 items), divide all counters in the grid by 2. 
      This decays old historical counts, naturally prioritizing recent frequency trends.
2. Bad for Low-Frequency Queries: While a Count-Min Sketch is exceptional at measuring highly frequent items, it is notoriously inaccurate for rare or low-frequency items. 
The collision noise from heavy-hitter elements will easily bleed into the slots of rare elements, making them appear far more frequent than they actually are.
3. No Way to Retrieve the Keys: The sketch stores counts, not names. You cannot iterate over a Count-Min Sketch to print out a list of all hashtags inside it. It can only answer questions
about keys you explicitly provide to it. This is why it must be paired with an auxiliary structure (like a Min-Heap) if your objective is to list the top trends.


HyperLogLog - 
A HyperLogLog (HLL) is a fixed-space, probabilistic data structure used to estimate the cardinality of a set—specifically, 
the number of unique elements (distinct values) in a massive dataset or stream.
If a Bloom Filter answers "Have I seen this?" and a Count-Min Sketch answers 
"How many times have I seen this?", HyperLogLog answers the question: "How many unique items are in this collection?"

Intuition
software engineer at a platform like YouTube or Netflix, and you need to calculate the number of unique daily active users (DAUs) watching videos.
1. The Naive Approach: Store every user ID in a standard HashSet or run a COUNT(DISTINCT user_id) query in a SQL database.
The Problem: If you have 500 million unique users, keeping a hash set of 500 million strings will consume gigabytes of RAM
2. The HyperLogLog Approach: Instead of storing the actual user IDs, you hash incoming user IDs
  It uses less than 1.5 KB of memory to count billions of unique items.
  It returns an estimate with a configurable standard error rate (typically around 1\% to 2\%).

How it Works
Step 1: The Hash Function Converts Data to Bits
When a user ID arrives (e.g., "user_104"), HyperLogLog passes it through a 64-bit hash function. This turns the text into a completely random-looking sequence of 0s and 1s.

Step 2: Splitting the Hash (Bucketing)To prevent a single "lucky" element from throwing off the entire count, HyperLogLog divides the work across multiple registers (called Buckets).It uses the first few bits of the hash string to decide which bucket this user belongs to.If we use the first
4 bits for bucketing, we have 2^4 = 16 possible buckets.Looking at our hash: 0010 is the binary representation of the number 2.Therefore, this user's data will be routed to Bucket #2.

Step 3: Counting the Leading Zeros
Now, HyperLogLog looks at the remaining bits of the hash string and counts how many consecutive 0s appear before hitting the first 1. This is where the coin-flipping logic happens.
Our remaining hash string starts with: 1000 0000 1101...
The very first bit is a 1.
This means there are 0 leading zeros.
What if a second user ("user_992") hashes to a string that puts them in Bucket #2 as well, but their remaining string looks like this?
0001 1100 0101...
This string has 3 leading zeros before hitting a 1.

Step 4: Updating the BucketEach bucket only stores one single number: the maximum number of leading zeros it has ever seen.Initially, Bucket #2 holds the value 0.When the first user arrives
(0 leading zeros), Bucket #2 stays at 0.When the second user arrives (3 leading zeros), HyperLogLog compares them. Since $3 > 0$, it overwrites the bucket. Bucket #2 now holds the number 3.

Step 5: Calculating the Total EstimateWhen you ask HyperLogLog for the total unique count, it doesn't look at the users (it already threw their names away). 
It only looks at the numbers inside its 16 buckets.If most buckets are holding low numbers 
like 0, 1, or 2, the math knows that very few unique users have visited.However, if it looks across the buckets and sees a few holding high numbers like 10 or 12,
the laws of probability state that you must have processed a massive amount of unique data to accidentally generate a hash string starting with 12 consecutive zeros
(1  in 4096 chance).
A standard HyperLogLog can use just 12,288 bits (1.5 KB) of total memory to keep track of billions of distinct items.
Here is the exact mathematical breakdown of how 12,288 bits handles massive cardinality.
1. Defining the Allocation: Buckets and BitsA standard production HyperLogLog configuration (like the one used natively in Redis) 
allocates 2^11 buckets Number of Buckets  = 2^{11} = 2,048 buckets
Each of these 2,048 buckets is allocated exactly 6 bits of memory space.Total Memory = 2,048 buckets times 6 bits/bucket= 12,288  bits
To convert bits to kilobytes:$12,288  bits div 8 = 1,536 bytes
1,536  bytes div 1,024 = 1.5 KB

how it determined how many DAU - 
The probability of a random hash starting with 5 zeros is $\frac{1}{2^5} = \frac{1}{32}$." Therefore, this single bucket expects that roughly 
32 unique items have been processed to hit that streak.If we generalize this, if a bucket holds a maximum zero-count of R, the raw estimated number of unique items seen by that bucket
is:Raw Estimate = 2^R
Why One Bucket Isn't Enough (The Fluke Problem)If you only look at one bucket, your estimate will be wildly inaccurate.Imagine the very first user visits your website. 
Their ID hashes to a string that randomly happens to start with 15 zeros purely by luck (a 1-in-32,768 chance). If you only had one bucket, it would instantly jump to 15, 
and your system would incorrectly claim you have 2^{15} = 32,768 users when you actually only have one.
To fix this, HyperLogLog divides your users across 2,048 independent buckets using the first 11 bits of their hash string.
Combining the Buckets (The Harmonic Mean)
Once all users are processed, HyperLogLog looks at the values in all 2,048 buckets. 
Instead of taking a normal average, it uses the Harmonic Mean.
A normal average (arithmetic mean) is easily ruined by a single "lucky" high number. The harmonic mean is a special mathematical average that heavily 
punishes huge outlier flukes while favoring the typical values in the group.
The Final Translation (The Magic Constant)Now we have an incredibly stable, fluke-resistant average of our exponential data. 
To turn this back into a human-readable estimate of unique users, HyperLogLog performs a final two-step calculation:
Step A: Scaling by Number of BucketsFirst, it multiplies the combined average by the total number of buckets m. 
This scales the estimate from "how many unique users went into each bucket" to "how many unique users hit the entire database":Scaled Estimate = m times Combined Average
Step B: Applying the Correction Factor alpha_m Because hashing and bucketing introduce a small, mathematically predictable bias, the result will
always be slightly off by a fixed ratio. To correct this, the algorithm multiplies the scaled estimate by a precise calibration constant called alpha_m. For 2,048 buckets, alpha_m = approx 0.7213.

Use-Cases and Pitfalls
1. Daily / Monthly Active Users (DAU / MAU)
2. Real-Time Ad Campaign Performance
Ad networks must track the number of unique impressions or clicks a specific ad receives across millions of concurrent users. 
Assigning a tiny 1.5 KB HyperLogLog sketch to each individual ad allows the system to scale tracking to millions of active campaigns simultaneously without memory strain.
3. 3. Database Query Optimizers
Modern relational databases (like PostgreSQL) and data warehouses use HyperLogLog underneath the hood to rapidly calculate column statistics (data distribution cardinality).

1. Inaccurate for Small Datasets: The harmonic mean formulas used by HLL are optimized for large-scale limits. 
On small datasets (e.g., fewer than a couple thousand unique items), standard HLL formulas produce severe estimation errors.
The Fix: Modern implementations use HyperLogLog++ (developed by Google). 
It detects small cardinalities and automatically falls back to utilizing linear counting or basic explicit sets until the data reaches a threshold where the core HLL algorithm stabilizes.
2. No Object Retrieval: HyperLogLog stores maximum zero counts inside structural registers, completely destroying the original data. 
You cannot ask HyperLogLog to output a list of the actual user IDs or usernames that visited your site. It can only tell you the total number of unique visitors.



95th percentile  - 
What is the 95th percentile ($p95$) of application response latency - 
p95 means that 95 of all application requests are faster than this value, while the remaining 5 are slower.
To find the $p95$ latency, the system takes those 100 response times and sorts them in an array from fastest to slowest:
The First 95 Requests (Fastest): These represent the normal, healthy experience for $95\%$ of your user base.
The 95th Request: The exact time taken by this specific request is your $p95$ threshold (e.g., 250ms).The Last 5 Requests (Slowest): 
These are the worst-performing requests (the "long tail" or outliers), taking anywhere from 500ms to 10 seconds due to network hiccups, database timeouts, or server load.

Approximate Quantiles sketch
The Naive Approach: Store every single latency value (e.g., millions of requests per second) in an array, sort it, and pick the value at index 0.99 times N.
The Problem: Keeping millions of floating-point numbers in memory or writing them to a database continuously 
will quickly consume all your RAM and disk I/O, crashing your monitoring tool.
The Approximate Quantiles Approach: You compress incoming numbers on the fly into smart, dynamic clusters.
To save massive amounts of memory, these structures guarantee that a quantile query (like p99) will be accurate within a strict precision threshold (e.g., 0.1 error).

2. How it Works (Using the T-Digest Algorithm)
Instead of saving every individual number, a T-Digest groups nearby data points into fluid, moving clusters called Centroids. Each centroid tracks two things:
The mean value of the points inside it.
The weight (the total number of data points it represents).

Centroids near the minimum and maximum edges of the dataset are forced to be very small 
(sometimes representing just a single data point). This preserves extreme precision for outliers.
Centroids near the center/median of the distribution are allowed to grow very large, swallowing thousands of points because slight approximation errors
in the middle of a bell curve don't heavily distort your percentiles.

Ingesting Data
As a continuous stream of values arrives:
The algorithm finds the closest existing centroid to the new value.
If adding the new value doesn't violate the size constraint for that centroid's position, the value is absorbed. The centroid's mean is 
recalculated dynamically, and its weight increases by 1.
If the centroid is already "full" based on its position in the distribution, a brand new centroid is initialized for that value.

Centroids at the extreme ends (the minimums and maximums) must be tiny, while centroids in the middle can be massive.At the edges (p0.1 or p99.9): 
The maximum weight allowed for a centroid might be just 1 or 2. The algorithm refuses to group numbers together here, forcing the sketch to remember the exact values 
of your worst-case outliers.
In the center (p50 / the median): The allowed weight explodes. It will happily let a single centroid swallow 50,000 points because when millions of users are getting 
a standard 10ms response time,
Ingesting a New Data Point
When a new number arrives in the stream (e.g., a new user API request takes 250ms):The sketch scans its sorted list of existing centroids to find 
the one whose Mean is closest to 250ms.It checks the rule: "If I add this new point to this centroid, will its weight exceed the size limit for this part of the scale?
"If No: It absorbs the point. The weight increments by 1, and the mean shifts slightly to accommodate the new number.
If Yes: (Because it's at the strict p99 edge), the sketch refuses to merge them. It creates a brand-new, independent centroid right at 250ms with a weight of 1.

Querying a Quantile : When you request a percentile (e.g., the $p95$ value):
The algorithm sorts the small collection of centroids by their mean values.It iterates through the weights to find where the 95th percentile mark falls.

Querying the Percentile (e.g., Finding p95)When you ask the system, "What is our p95 latency right now?", 
it executes a quick calculation:It lays out all the centroids in a straight line, sorted by their Mean values from lowest to highest.
It sums up all the Weights to find the total number of points processed (let's say the total weight is 100,000).It counts through the weights until it hits the 95% mark (the 95,000th point).
If the 95,000th point falls right between Centroid A (Mean = 240ms) and Centroid B (Mean = 260ms), it uses standard linear interpolation 
(a mathematical straight-line estimate) between those two points to confidently return an answer like 244.5ms.

Use cases:
1. SLA Monitoring and Alerts (DevOps & Infrastructure)
An average latency metric is deceptive—if 90% of your users experience a 10ms load time but 10% experience a 10-second timeout, 
the average looks healthy, but your customers are leaving. Tracking $p95$ and $p99$ using a quantile sketch catches these issues instantly.
2. Database Query Optimization (Histograms)
Modern distributed execution engines use quantile sketches to build data distribution histograms for partition columns. Knowing where the $p25, p50,$ and $p75$
boundaries reside allows a database planner to distribute workloads evenly across cluster nodes, preventing data skew.


